    <!-- FAQs -->
    <section id="faq" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I change employers on my work visa?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Yes, but you need a "No Objection Certificate" (NOC) from your current employer, or you must have completed 2 years with them (or 1 year for skilled workers earning AED 5,000+). Without NOC, you may face a 6-12 month work ban.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens to my visa if I'm terminated?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">You have 30 days to find new employment or exit the UAE. Your employer must cancel your visa. During this grace period, you can job search on a visit visa. If you don't find work, you must leave.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is my family covered under my employer's insurance?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Usually no. Most employers only cover the employee. You'll need to sponsor dependents (requires minimum salary of AED 4,000/month for family visa) and arrange their insurance separately or negotiate family coverage in your contract.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the difference between mainland and free zone employment?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Free zones (DIFC, DMCC, JAFZA, etc.) are special economic areas with different regulations. Visa processing may be faster, but you may face restrictions on doing business outside the free zone. Insurance requirements are the same.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I apply for Golden Visa on an employment visa?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Yes, if you earn AED 30,000+/month or hold a specialized role (scientists, doctors, engineers, artists). Golden Visa gives you 10-year residence without needing employer sponsorship, plus you can sponsor family.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if I fail the medical test?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Testing positive for HIV, TB, or Hepatitis B/C typically results in visa denial and deportation orders. TB cases may be allowed to undergo treatment and retest. Appeals are possible but rarely successful. Get tested before accepting a UAE offer if you're uncertain.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Final Verdict -->
    <section id="verdict" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        The UAE work visa offers tax-free income, world-class infrastructure, and a strategic location bridging East and West. The employer sponsorship system means your visa is tied to your job, which creates both security (employer handles paperwork) and dependency (changing jobs has restrictions).
      </p>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        Health insurance is genuinely mandatory and enforced. Your employer must provide it, but coverage quality varies enormously. Basic plans meet legal requirements but may leave you exposed for serious conditions, dental work, or treatment outside UAE. Understanding exactly what your employer plan covers—and its limits—is essential before you relocate.
      </p>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        For families, plan carefully. Dependent sponsorship, schooling, and family health insurance add significant costs that your tax-free salary should easily cover—but only if you budget correctly. The 0% income tax is real and substantial, making the UAE financially attractive even with private insurance and school fees.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-2">Bottom Line</h3>
        <p class="text-primary-800">The UAE work visa is excellent for career growth and wealth-building if you accept the trade-offs: employer visa dependency, strict medical testing, and navigating a private healthcare system. Supplement basic employer insurance if you have health concerns or family. The Golden Visa pathway now offers long-term security for high earners who want to stay.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

